'''Uwato Shrine''' (うわとじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Akeno-chō, {{ill|lt=Hokuto|Q825272|WD=Q825272|1=Hokuto, Yamanashi}}, {{ill|lt=Yamanashi Prefecture|Q132720|WD=Q132720|1=Yamanashi Prefecture}}. Its deities are {{ill|WD=Q9150391|lt=Takeminakata|Q9150391|WD=Q9150391|WD=Q9150391|lt=Takeminakata-no-Mikoto|1=Takeminakata}}, {{ill|lt=Izanagi|Q813858|WD=Q813858|lt=Izanagi-no-Mikoto|1=Izanagi}}, {{ill|lt=Izanami|Q682306|WD=Q682306|lt=Izanami-no-Mikoto|1=Izanami}}, {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|WD=Q272993|lt=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}}, and {{ill|WD=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama|Q3080728|WD=Q3080728|WD=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto|1=Ukanomitama}}<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|和書 |title=Akeno Village History, main volume |edition=new edition |date=March 1996 |publisher=Akeno Village |pages=859,1267}}</ref>. Festival days are April 10 and October 5. The April grand annual festival date has been changed to the 2nd Sunday of April<ref>{{Cite book|和書 |title=Festivals and rites of Yamanashi - investigation report - |date=March 1999 |publisher=Yamanashi Prefectural Board of Education |page=125}}</ref>.

=== History ===
The founding era is unknown. However, a stone {{ill|lt=torii|Q234731|WD=Q234731|1=Torii}} bears inscription "{{ill|lt=Jōgan|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|lt=Jōgan|1=Jōgan}} 6 ({{ill|lt=864|Q25041|WD=Q25041|1=864}})," and the shrine is treated as an Engishiki {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, so it is inferred to have existed at least by the {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1374325|WD=Q1374325|1=Engi (era)}} period ({{ill|lt=901|Q23580|WD=Q23580|1=901}}-{{ill|lt=923|Q30108|WD=Q30108|1=923}})<ref name="観光">[https://www.yamanashi-kankou.jp/rekitabi/jisha/spot/130.html Uwato Shrine] Yamanashi Tourism Organization "Travel Yamanashi history"</ref><ref name="散歩">Yamanashi Prefecture High School History/Civics Research Group (ed.), 'Historical Walk in Yamanashi' (Historical Walk 19), Yamakawa Shuppansha, 2007, pp.186-187</ref>.

It is also known that {{ill|lt=Takeda Shingen|Q276404|WD=Q276404|1=Takeda Shingen}} prayed here for victory during his Saku campaign ({{ill|lt=Battle of Odaibara|Q1056249|WD=Q1056249|1=Battle of Odaihara}})<ref name="観光"/>.

The current haiden was rebuilt in April 1980, and the kaguraden was newly built<ref>{{Cite book|和書 |title=Yamanashi Prefecture Shrine Gazetteer |date=Sept 1985 |publisher=Yamanashi Shinto Youth Association |page=287}}</ref>.

This shrine has a stone torii. It is Myōjin-style and the only one of that form in former Akeno Village<ref name=":0" />. Its height is 2.52 {{ill|lt=meters|Q11573|WD=Q11573|1=Metre}}, but pillar diameter is as much as 43 {{ill|lt=centimeters|Q174728|WD=Q174728|1=Centimetre}}, giving a stout appearance. Built in the {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}}, it is considered one of the oldest torii in Japan<ref name=":0" /><ref name="散歩"/>. Similar torii exists at {{ill|lt=Katte Shrine (Nirasaki)|Q116979329|WD=Q116979329|lt=Katte Shrine|1=Katte Shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Nirasaki|Q290326|WD=Q290326|1=Nirasaki, Yamanashi}}, same prefecture.

=== Precinct ===
Within the precinct are the honden, haiden, kaguraden, watariden, and shamusho<ref name=":0" />.
